PERIODIC CHOLERA REPORT
AFRICA
Burundi
Date: 2 Apr 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The MASTA Report [edited

An outbreak of cholera has been reported in Bujumbura. Outbreaks are
reported sporadically throughout the country. Over 100 cases of typhoid
fever were reported in Bururi province in the southwest last year.
Travelers are reminded to take particular care with food and water hygiene.
Boil or purify all drinking water. Cholera immunization is not recommended
by the WHO as a means of personal protection. It is advisable to be [up to
date for typhoid immunization.
******
Democratic Republic of Congo
Date: 2 Apr 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The MASTA Report [edited

The collapsed infrastructure and contaminated water supplies are thought to
have contributed to the spread of cholera and typhoid: 685 cases of cholera
have been reported in Goma (eastern regions of the country). Travelers
should take care with food and water hygiene. Water should be boiled or
purified. Iodine resin water purifiers are recommended. The WHO does not
recommend cholera immunization for personal protection.
******
Kenya
Date: 3 Apr 2001
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: East African Standard [edited

At least 2 people from Kikambala division have died of cholera while
several others are hospitalized. A subchief in Mtwapa, Mr Simeon Ngome,
confirmed one death and said more than 22 people are in hospital. He made
the remarks at a public baraza at Kikambala trading centre.
The worst hit areas are Junju, Kulewa and Gongoni, he said at the weekend
function. The 22 patients are admitted at Vipingo Health Centre. Medical
personnel have been deployed to the area to contain the spread of the
disease, Ngome said.
He cautioned residents against using unboiled water and eating half-cooked
food. He also advised them to use pit latrines to curb the spread of the
disease. He said the disease had earlier been reported in the neighboring
Kisauni location and it is quickly spreading to Kikambala.
******
Somalia
Date: 10 May 2001
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: News Media [edited

A joint UNICEF, World Health Organisation (WHO) and COSVI (Italian NGO)
team is investigating cases of suspected cholera recently reported in
southern Somalia, from Qoryoley District in Lower Shabelle Region,
humanitarian sources have told IRIN.
In March, a cholera outbreak was reported in the coastal town of Marka,
along with several other outbreaks in southern Somalia since the start of
the year. UNICEF Somalia said the cumulative figure up until mid-April for
cases in these outbreaks was 881, with 71 deaths confirmed -- a case
fatality rate of 8.1 percent.
As of 2 May, no positive confirmation of cholera in 2 cases from 2 separate
villages was made by the team, UNICEF said. Medical supplies and chlorine
have been pre-positioned in Qoryoley, and the team is investigating another
case in Gobale village, Lower Shabelle. Humanitarian sources told IRIN that
recent reports of cholera in Wanle Weyne, Lower Shabelle, had been
"exaggerated", and confused with other diarrheal diseases.
With the onset of the rainy season, a rise of diarrheal diseases was
expected, said the source, but not cholera. Cholera is endemic in Somalia
and, although appearing with different outbreaks every year, is typically
associated with the dry season from December through to May, according to a
UNICEF fact sheet. Regarding cholera and other diarrhoeal diseases in
Somalia, it says Somalia's infant mortality and under five mortality rates
"remain among the highest in the world." Diarrheal disease, acute
respiratory infections, tuberculosis and malaria are still the leading
causes of death for infants and young children in Somalia, accounting for
more than half of all child deaths.
******
South Africa
Date: 5 May 2001
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Nando Times [edited

A cholera epidemic has broken out in a coastal prison in South Africa,
officials said Friday, and 500 inmates have fallen ill with diarrhea,
vomiting, and dehydration. The outbreak began Tuesday in the
maximum-security section of Westville Prison after an inmate was admitted
with the highly contagious disease, according to Russel Mamabolo, a
spokesman for the corrections department. Mamabolo told the South African
Press Association that said steps were being taken to contain the disease
and that all prisoners entering or leaving the prison would be screened for
cholera. One of the affected prisoners was in serious condition.
***
Date: 4 Jun 2001
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: AP Online [edited

CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- The number of people infected by a cholera
outbreak in South Africa broke the 100 000 mark Monday, and authorities
said there was no end in sight to the epidemic.
Since it surfaced last August, the highly infectious, waterborne disease
has killed 208 people in the country's southeast, mostly poor rural
dwellers without access to clean water and proper sanitation in
KwaZulu-Natal province. "From the word go, a lot of experts were saying to
us (cholera) is going to be with us for the next 2 to 3 years," said Dave
McGlew, the KwaZulu-Natal health department's head of communications. "We
are not making any predictions, but that seems accurate."
In the early 1980s, South Africa's worst cholera epidemic infected more
than 105 400 people over a 4-year period. More than 340 people died.
Although the number of new cases is declining, the current epidemic
continues to infect up to 250 people a day. Provincial health authorities
said Monday 100 028 people had been infected since August.
McGlew said necessary facilities were now in place to manage the disease at
the province's 60 hospitals and 450 clinics, while mobile hydration
facilities were serving remote communities. To date less than 0.3 percent
of those infected have died. The mortality rate is one of the lowest ever
recorded. Scientists are unsure what caused cholera to become dormant and
then flare up again, but say that until people have access to clean running
water and proper sanitation it is certain to recur. About 7 million South
Africans -- 16 percent of the population -- still do not have access to
clean water, and about 18 million people do not have acceptable sanitation,
according to government statistics.
[Byline: Mike Cohen
*****
Date: 27 Jun 2001
From: Marjorie P. Pollack, M.D. <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited

A total of 126 new Cholera cases were reported on Wednesday in the infected
eastern province of KwaZulu-Natal, according to the provincial health
department. However, no more deaths were reported and the death toll
remained at 212, the department said in a statement. The total number of
cases reported since the outbreak of the disease last August has increased
to 103 320. The new cases showed that the disease has not been brought
under control despite extensive efforts to contain the scourge, health
officials said. The disease is mostly confined to the KwaZulu-Natal
Province, which has poorer water sanitation and more impoverished people.
[This is a huge ongoing outbreak. Or perhaps better said, it's an outbreak
in an area with good epidemiologic surveillance, so there's a higher
proportion of cases being captured by the system. - Mod.CM
