CENTRAL ASIA
Nepal
Date: 25 June 2001
From: Marjorie P. Pollack, M.D. <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited

KATHMANDU, 26 Jun 2001 -- More than 75 people have died of gastroenteritis
epidemic in the far-flung Bajhang and Doti districts in far western Nepal
since the monsoon season began early this month, according to reports
reaching here Tuesday. Among the dead, most are elderly people, women and
infants, while hundreds of others are suffering from the disease that
normally spreads due to consumption of contaminated water and poor
sanitation, the Kathmandu Post, an English daily, quoted local hospital
sources as saying.
Another reason behind the heavy death toll is the geographic
inaccessibility that hinders locals from taking the sick to the nearest
health center and the district hospital, Pitambar Subedi, chief at the
District Hospital of Bajhang district, was quoted as saying. Subedi said
this is the largest ever death toll from the epidemic in the region during
the last 6 years, and the death toll could increase because the affected
areas are located far away from district headquarters, where people can be
treated with better medication. Medical teams are expected to be sent to
the affected areas soon to control the spread of the epidemics, the daily said.
******
SOUTH ASIA
China
Date: 26 Jun 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Agence France Presse English 26 Jun 2001 [edited

HONG KONG (AFP) -- An area in Shenzhen, at the border with Hong Kong, has
been cordoned off following an outbreak of cholera, a report said Tuesday.
Dapeng, in Shenzhen's Longgang district, has been off limits since Monday
after more than 60 people were said to have contracted the disease.
Several people have died, the Chinese-language Oriental Daily News said.
Authorities denied the outbreak was cholera, saying the victims were
suffering gastroenteritis.
The report said that living conditions in Dapeng, 7 kilometers (4.34 miles)
from Daya nuclear power plants in eastern coastal Shenzhen, were poor, and
there were no toilets in some of the houses. The town is home to some 600
people who are mostly migrant workers from Sichuan, Hunan, and Guangxi
provinces, and who work in factories run by Hong Kong and overseas firms,
the report said.
A similar cholera outbreak was recently reported in Zhanjiang, 450
kilometers (279 miles) southwest of Shenzhen, where more than 100 people
have reportedly contracted cholera. Of the 8 confirmed cholera cases in
Hong Kong this year, one was an imported case in May, 6 were local cases
reported in June, and the most recent case has yet to be classified.
******
Malaysia
Date: 16 May 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters News Agency [edited
KUALA LUMPUR - Health authorities in Malaysia's Selangor state said on
Wednesday they have contained a cholera outbreak near the capital Kuala
Lumpur that has killed one person. Since the first person was diagnosed 2
weeks ago in Meru, a town 35 km (22 miles) southwest of Kuala Lumpur, 93
other cases have been confirmed. The authorities have closed down 136 food
stalls after fingering a favorite local snack, "nasi lemak," made from
coconut-flavored rice, as the most likely source of the outbreak. The
victim, a 21-year-old Meru man, died on 7 May 2001 after 3 days in
hospital. In an outbreak in nearby Bangi town in early December, which was
traced to a factory canteen, 9 cases were confirmed. In 1996 more than 800
people were hit by cholera during an epidemic centered in northern Penang
state. No deaths were reported.
******
DIARRHEA AND DYSENTERY REPORT
East Timor
Date: 9 April 2001
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Australian Broadcast Corp [edited

A Catholic aid group says dozens of East Timorese refugees are dying from a
rapidly spreading diarrhea epidemic in camps in Indonesian-ruled West Timor.
The Jesuit Refugee Service says the outbreak is spreading quickly at a camp
near the capital Kupang. Malnutrition is also claiming lives, and it says
there have been no rice supplies to the camps since January. All foreign
aid workers fled West Timor after three UN refugee workers were killed in
their office in the border town of Atambua by an pro-Jakarta militia mob in
September. A UN delegation is in West Timor this week to gather information
on the refugees and encourage them to return home.
******
Ghana
Date: 9 April 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Africa News Service

Cases of typhoid fever have been reported in the Greater Accra Region in
Ghana, the "Daily Graphic" newspaper reported the Ministry of Health as
saying in a statement on Friday. The ministry said reported cases of the
disease were on the increase and many people had been admitted to
hospitals. Adding that it was investigating the cause of the outbreak, it
advised the public to drink water from safe sources and not to eat at
unhygienic establishments. Up to mid-afternoon on Monday no official
statement had been released on the number of people killed or affected by
the outbreaks, Abigail Bonsu, a journalist at the newspaper, told IRIN.
Typhoid fever is transmitted by food and water contaminated by the feces
and urine of patients and carriers. Polluted water is the most common
source of typhoid.
